# personal-mac-mcp-host/.env.example
#
# Copy to .env (sibling file, gitignored), fill in your own values, then
# run personal-mcp-host.sh (or load the LaunchAgent — see README.md).
#
#   cp .env.example .env
#   $EDITOR .env
#
# ===== Required =====

# Remote host the MacBook dials out to (the host that runs your *other*
# Claude Code instance). DNS name or IP. Must accept SSH from this Mac
# under SSH_KEY_PATH below.
REMOTE_HOST="your-remote-host.example.com"

# Remote SSH user. Must have an entry in ~/.ssh/authorized_keys on
# REMOTE_HOST for the public half of SSH_KEY_PATH.
REMOTE_USER="yourname"

# Port the reverse tunnel binds on REMOTE_HOST's loopback. The remote
# Claude reaches the MacBook's MCP server by dialing
# localhost:$REMOTE_PORT on REMOTE_HOST. Pick an unused high port.
REMOTE_PORT="18766"

# Port mcp-host-bash binds on the MacBook's loopback. The reverse tunnel
# forwards REMOTE_PORT -> 127.0.0.1:$MCP_LOCAL_PORT on this side. Default
# 8766 matches the compose-stack default; change if 8766 is taken on the
# Mac (e.g. the compose-stack launcher is also running).
MCP_LOCAL_PORT="8766"

# Private SSH key the tunnel uses. STRONGLY RECOMMEND a dedicated key
# (not your daily ed25519) so the remote can restrict it to
# port-forward-only via authorized_keys options — see the SSH key
# hardening section of README.md.
SSH_KEY_PATH="$HOME/.ssh/id_personal_mcp_tunnel"

# ===== Optional =====

# Shared-secret bearer token for the MCP server's auth shim. STRONGLY
# RECOMMENDED even though the tunnel is SSH-encrypted, because anything
# else on REMOTE_HOST's loopback can also dial localhost:$REMOTE_PORT —
# the bearer is the defense-in-depth layer that bounds access to
# callers who have the secret.
#
# Generate once:
#
#   head -c 32 /dev/urandom | base64
#
# The remote-side MCP client must send the SAME value as an
# `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header (see "Remote-side MCP client
# config" in README.md). Leave empty to disable the shim — operators
# who trust the remote's loopback (e.g. single-user homelab box) can
# go without, at their discretion.
MCP_HOST_BASH_BEARER=""

# Trust profile for mcp-host-bash's allow-list. Default `corp-dev`
# (read-y dev-tooling floor — file inspection, text munging, VCS,
# language toolchains, read-only network probes). Set
# `corp-dev-trusted` to widen to host scheduling, file mutation,
# outbound bytes, and container management.
#
# Pick `corp-dev` (the default) unless you specifically need the
# remote-side Claude to mutate files / fire webhooks / manage
# containers on the Mac. See examples/compose/bin/mcp-host-bash header
# for the full per-profile surface.
CW_PROFILE="corp-dev"

# Fence run_command to this directory. mcp-host-bash's default is /
# (path boundary DISABLED). Setting this (e.g. $HOME, or
# $HOME/personal-mcp-scratch) RE-ENABLES a directory fence and limits
# the blast radius if a remote-side Claude misbehaves.
#
# Leave commented out to inherit the open / default from mcp-host-bash.
# ALLOWED_DIR="$HOME"

# Let run_command chain pipes / && / redirects. Default false. Loosens
# the safety floor; only set to `true` if a specific workflow needs it.
# ALLOW_SHELL_OPERATORS="false"

# ===== Advanced =====

# Absolute path to mcp-host-bash launcher. Default: the sibling repo
# path (examples/compose/bin/mcp-host-bash relative to this script).
# Override if your mcp-host-bash lives outside this checkout.
# MCP_HOST_BASH_BIN="$HOME/code/claude-watch/examples/compose/bin/mcp-host-bash"

# Extra `ssh -o KEY=VALUE` options appended to the tunnel argv. Use for
# one-off tuning without editing personal-mcp-host.sh. Examples:
#   - PERSONAL_MCP_SSH_EXTRA="-o ProxyJump=bastion.example.com"
#   - PERSONAL_MCP_SSH_EXTRA="-o ServerAliveInterval=15"
# Space-separated; values themselves cannot contain whitespace.
# PERSONAL_MCP_SSH_EXTRA=""

# Soft kill switch. Set to 1 to have personal-mcp-host.sh exit 0
# immediately. Pair with launchd's KeepAlive to leave the unit
# registered without actually running the bridge.
# PERSONAL_MCP_DISABLED="0"
